<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-10-31T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-10-31T05:00:00-05:00" n="704" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d704">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115/505: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Josselyn</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-10-31T18:00:00+08:00">October 31, 1938—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received October 31—10:14 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Japanese military and naval authorities are proceeding in an apparently
                            orderly manner to occupy property for their use. Representatives from
                                <hi rend="italic">gendarmerie</hi> headquarters called yesterday and
                            were allowed to copy data from the map in possession of this office
                            showing American owned property insofar as it had been reported to this
                            office. A memorandum was handed to them at the same time stating that
                            the map did not purport to show all American owned or occupied property
                            and making reservation of rights.</p>
                        <p>Sent to Chungking, Peiping.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Josselyn</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>